Comment:
This was the cutest comedy I've ever seen! Wait. . .this was supposed to be a horror film??
 I'm sorry, but no clown will ever be as despair-inflicting and psychotically intimidating as Heath Ledger's Joker. He actually didn't give a rip when someone didn't fear him but thrived off of people realizing what darkness they truly were under the fake smiles. Unlike this Pennywise, Joker had no limits that little kids could easily find to beat him with. No, Joker (not the Leto) would've given the town the small push of gravity  that would've properly sent them into the chaos that Pennywise failed at trying to accomplish. The real believable monsters are those that can show the audience that they really aren't that different from them. #Hewasthebetterclassofcriminal

As I was watching the movie, I admired the great story, the charming cinematography, the marvelous score, and the friendly performances lead by Jaeden Lieberher, Finn Wolfhard, Jack Dylan Grazer, and Wyatt Oleff to name a few. To me, It felt more like a charming adaptation of a coming of age novel like Holes, or The Outsiders because I was disappointed that director Andy Muschietti didn‚Äôt let the horror elements reach their full potential like Matt Reeves did with Let Me In or like Sam Raimi did with the birth of Doc Ock scene in Spider-Man 2. The scares in It are too light, but that being said, Bill Skarsg√•rd gives an outstanding performance as It / Pennywise the Dancing Clown. He‚Äôs the most vile and hostile villain I‚Äôve seen since Steve Carell‚Äôs interpretation of John du Pont in the fascinating drama Foxcatcher. 3 out of 5 stars.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
*No Spoilers*
Derry, ME, October 1988 - Bill Denbrough (Jaeden Lieberher) helps his little brother Georgie (Jackson Robert Scott) make a paper sailboat, calling it the S.S. Georgie. Georgie wants to go outside to sail it in the pouring rain, but Bill is too sick to join him. The brothers hug before Georgie runs out to play.

Georgie sails his boat down the street. He chases after it and accidentally runs into a roadblock. The boat sails to the end of the street until it falls into the sewer. Georgie runs to try and get it, worried that Bill will be mad. As he looks into the sewer, a pair of yellow eyes emerge. They belong to an entity calling itself Pennywise the dancing clown (Bill Skarsgard). Pennywise playfully speaks to Georgie before offering him his boat back. Georgie reaches for it, only for Pennywise to grab his arm and sink his massive teeth into it. The creature rips off Georgie's arm and leaves him crying for Bill before dragging him down into the sewers.

June 1989 - We meet Mike Hanlon (Chosen Jacobs) as his grandfather Leroy (Steven Williams) is making him kill a sheep with a nail gun. Leroy lectures the boy before doing the deed himself.

It's the last day of school. Bill and his friend Richie Tozier (Finn Wolfhard), Eddie Kaspbrak (Jack Dylan Grazer), and Stanley Uris (Wyatt Oleff), who all form The Losers Club, are heading out to start their summer. Unfortunately, they run into the school's psychopathic bully Henry Bowers (Nicholas Hamilton) and his goons Patrick Hockstetter (Owen Teague), Victor Criss (Logan Thompson), and Belch Huggins (Jake Sim). Bill tells Henry he sucks after the punk mocks his friends, and Henry approaches Bill threateningly until he sees his father, Officer Bowers (Stuart Hughes), standing behind Bill. He walks away, but not before licking his palm and smearing it on Bill's face.

A girl named Beverly Marsh (Sophia Lillis) is smoking in the bathroom. A group of mean girls led by Gretta (Megan Charpentier) taunt her and accuse Bev of being a slut. One girl fills a trash bag full of water and dumps it on Bev, but she covers her head with her book. On her way out of the building, Beverly meets the new kid, Ben Hascom (Jeremy Ray Taylor). He gets picked on for his weight and he doesn't have friends. Bev signs his yearbook, and Ben appears to develop a crush on her.

When Bill gets home, his father Zach (Geoffrey Pounsett) scolds him for creating a model with tubes of the sewer system in Derry since he still believes that Georgie is only missing. Zach tells him to accept that Georgie is dead.

Mike goes to the butcher shop to make a delivery. Behind the door around the alley, he hears what sounds like screaming and pounding. The door opens and several burnt hands start sticking out. Mike then sees Pennywise, but is nearly run over by the Bowers gang in a car. Mike flees.

Stan is at the synagogue studying for his bar mitzvah. There is a painting in the rabbi's office that creeps him out showing a woman with a distorted face. The painting falls, and when Stan picks it up, the woman is gone. He turns around and IT manifests as the woman with a fanged smile. Stan runs away.

Ben is at the library looking up Derry's history. From a series of articles, he learns that children in Derry have been disappearing under mysterious circumstances for centuries. The book contains a depiction of Pennywise and a missing boy's head in a tree. Ben is then lured into the basement where he sees the headless boy before getting chased out by Pennywise.

On his way home, Ben is attacked by the Bowers gang. Henry's goons hold him against the bridge railing. Patrick wants to burn Ben with a lighter and bug spray, but Henry plans to carve his name into Ben's stomach. An old couple drive by and see this but do nothing (it's implied that IT is there with the presence of a red balloon). Henry only cuts an H before Ben kicks him in the nuts and rolls over the bridge and into the woods. The punks chase after Ben. Meanwhile, the Losers are near the sewers as Bill has convinced his friends to help him find Georgie. Ben falls into the water near them, and the boys grab him and bring him to safety.

Patrick runs into the sewers to try and get Ben, splitting from his friends. He encounters demonic-looking children that make him run, but he comes across a dead end. A bunch of red balloons appear before him, and they all pop to reveal Pennywise, who promptly devours Patrick.

The boys go to the pharmacy to get cotton balls and bandages, but they are short on money. Beverly is there buying tampons when she runs into the boys. After hearing their problem, Bev pretends to flirt with the pharmacist, Mr. Keene (Joe Bostick), to distract him. He comes off as a creep to her, but she manages to distract him long enough for the boys to steal their supplies, and for her to sneak away some cigarettes. Bev goes outside and joins the boys when she sees the boys tending to Ben.

Beverly goes home to her father (Stephen Bogaert), who is an even bigger creep than Mr. Keene. He comes onto his daughter, causing her to run into the bathroom crying. She then proceeds to cut off her hair until it's at a shorter length.

The boys (now joined by Ben) are at the quarry ready to jump into the lake, but no one is eager to go first. Bev shows up and jumps first, leading the others to join. They have fun while swimming and hanging out. Later, Ben tells everyone what he read about in Derry's history.

Eddie is walking home when he passes the abandoned house on Neibolt Street. He is suddenly attacked by a leper (Javier Botet), causing Eddie to run through the house's yard. As he reaches the fence, he sees Pennywise trying to lure him toward him. Eddie runs under the fence and escapes.

Bev is in her room with a postcard with a poem written on it by a secret admirer. She thinks it's Bill but it was actually Ben that wrote it. From her bathroom, Bev hears the voices of children. She looks into the sink where the voices are, and clumps of hair start reaching out to grab her before a fountain of blood gushes all over the bathroom. Mr. Marsh comes in to see Bev horrified, but he cannot see the blood. He simply comments that her hair makes her look like a boy.

Bill is walking around the house when he sees what looks like Georgie running around. Shocked, he follows Georgie to the basement, which is flooding. Georgie steps out and invites Bill to join him, saying "We all float down here. You'll float too." He repeats "You'll float too" until he yells and decomposes. Pennywise then emerges from the water and tries to get Bill, but he runs out of the basement.

The next day, the kids are riding their bikes when they see Mike's bike and the Bowers gang's car. They go down by the creek to find the punks harassing Mike for being black. Bev throws a rock at Henry's head, which initiates a rock-throwing war between both groups. Mike runs over to the Losers side while Vic and Belch run away as Henry is knocked unconscious.

As the kids walk away with Mike, Bill mentions what he saw in his house. Eddie backs him up on having seen Pennywise. Mike mentions what he saw and talks about how his old house was burnt down by racist goons, and his parents died trying to break the door down to his room, with their skin having melted to the bone. Richie is the only one that hasn't been haunted, but he admits to being terrified of clowns.

The kids go to Bill's garage where they look over a map of Derry through a projector. They see that the sewers are linked to the Neibolt house, where IT lives. The projector then starts working itself, showing pictures of Bill and Georgie with their parents, but with Pennywise's face appearing over their mother. They knock the projector over, but it keeps playing until Pennywise fully emerges from the screen and tries to get the kids. They manage to get out of the garage before he can harm them.

The Losers go to the Neibolt house to face IT head-on. Bill, Richie, and Eddie enter the house while the others stay outside as lookouts. Richie sees a missing poster of himself and he freaks out, but Bill reminds him it's not real. Eddie gets separated from his friends when Pennywise finds him. He falls through the floor and lands in the kitchen, breaking his arm. Bill and Richie try to reach him through three doors. The first door they open reveals a headless girl. The second door traps Richie inside with a room full of clown dolls. He sees a coffin with a dummy of himself in it. He shuts it, and Pennywise jumps out. He tries to attack Richie, but he runs out of the room. Pennywise returns his attention to Eddie, but Bill and Richie get to him before the clown eats him. Beverly then shows up to drive a spear through Pennywise's head, forcing him to retreat.

Eddie's mom forbids the Losers from hanging out with him after she sees his broken arm. Bill and Richie then get into a fight when Richie says this whole pursuit of Georgie has nearly gotten them killed. The Losers part ways as the other boys are too terrified to keep going.

It's now August, and the kids have continued going about their lives. Eddie goes to the pharmacy to pick up his asthma medication, only for Gretta (who works behind the counter) to tell him that they are placebos. She then writes "LOSER" on his arm cast.

Henry is with Vic and Belch shooting things with his dad's gun. He orders Belch to bring him a cat to shoot, but Officer Bowers shows up to take the gun from Henry. He then shoots the ground around Henry's feet to humiliate him in front of his friends and expose him as a coward. Later, Henry sees a red balloon on his mailbox. Inside is a knife, sent by IT. He goes inside as his father is asleep with the TV on. On the screen appears a woman with children, all urging Henry to kill his father. He does so by sticking the knife in his neck and letting him bleed out. The kids on TV (all of IT's victims) then start chanting "KILL THEM ALL! KILL THEM ALL!"

At the Marsh

Beverly goes home to her father (Stephen Bogaert), who is an even bigger creep than Mr. Keene. He comes onto his daughter, causing her to run into the bathroom crying. She then proceeds to cut off her hair until it's at a shorter length.

The boys (now joined by Ben) are at the quarry ready to jump into the lake, but no one is eager to go first. Bev shows up and jumps first, leading the others to join. They have fun while swimming and hanging out. Later, Ben tells everyone what he read about in Derry's history.

Eddie is walking home when he passes the abandoned house on Neibolt Street. He is suddenly attacked by a leper (Javier Botet), causing Eddie to run through the house's yard. As he reaches the fence, he sees Pennywise trying to lure him toward him. Eddie runs under the fence and escapes.

Bev is in her room with a postcard with a poem written on it by a secret admirer. She thinks it's Bill but it was actually Ben that wrote it. From her bathroom, Bev hears the voices of children. She looks into the sink where the voices are, and clumps of hair start reaching out to grab her before a fountain of blood gushes all over the bathroom. Mr. Marsh comes in to see Bev horrified, but he cannot see the blood. He simply comments that her hair makes her look like a boy.

Bill is walking around the house when he sees what looks like Georgie running around. Shocked, he follows Georgie to the basement, which is flooding. Georgie steps out and invites Bill to join him, saying "We all float down here. You'll float too." He repeats "You'll float too" until he yells and decomposes. Pennywise then emerges from the water and tries to get Bill, but he runs out of the basement.

The next day, the kids are riding their bikes when they see Mike's bike and the Bowers gang's car. They go down by the creek to find the punks harassing Mike for being black. Bev throws a rock at Henry's head, which initiates a rock-throwing war between both groups. Mike runs over to the Losers side while Vic and Belch run away as Henry is knocked unconscious.

As the kids walk away with Mike, Bill mentions what he saw in his house. Eddie backs him up on having seen Pennywise. Mike mentions what he saw and talks about how his old house was burnt down by racist goons, and his parents died trying to break the door down to his room, with their skin having melted to the bone. Richie is the only one that hasn't been haunted, but he admits to being terrified of clowns.

The kids go to Bill's garage where they look over a map of Derry through a projector. They see that the sewers are linked to the Neibolt house, where IT lives. The projector then starts working itself, showing pictures of Bill and Georgie with their parents, but with Pennywise's face appearing over their mother. They knock the projector over, but it keeps playing until Pennywise fully emerges from the screen and tries to get the kids. They manage to get out of the garage before he can harm them.

The Losers go to the Neibolt house to face IT head-on. Bill, Richie, and Eddie enter the house while the others stay outside as lookouts. Richie sees a missing poster of himself and he freaks out, but Bill reminds him it's not real. Eddie gets separated from his friends when Pennywise finds him. He falls through the floor and lands in the kitchen, breaking his arm. Bill and Richie try to reach him through three doors. The first door they open reveals a headless girl. The second door traps Richie inside with a room full of clown dolls. He sees a coffin with a dummy of himself in it. He shuts it, and Pennywise jumps out. He tries to attack Richie, but he runs out of the room. Pennywise returns his attention to Eddie, but Bill and Richie get to him before the clown eats him. Beverly then shows up to drive a spear through Pennywise's head, forcing him to retreat.

Eddie's mom forbids the Losers from hanging out with him after she sees his broken arm. Bill and Richie then get into a fight when Richie says this whole pursuit of Georgie has nearly gotten them killed. The Losers part ways as the other boys are too terrified to keep going.

It's now August, and the kids have continued going about their lives. Eddie goes to the pharmacy to pick up his asthma medication, only for Gretta (who works behind the counter) to tell him that they are placebos. She then writes "LOSER" on his arm cast.

Henry is with Vic and Belch shooting things with his dad's gun. He orders Belch to bring him a cat to shoot, but Officer Bowers shows up to take the gun from Henry. He then shoots the ground around Henry's feet to humiliate him in front of his friends and expose him as a coward. Later, Henry sees a red balloon on his mailbox. Inside is a knife, sent by IT. He goes inside as his father is asleep with the TV on. On the screen appears a woman with children, all urging Henry to kill his father. He does so by sticking the knife in his neck and letting him bleed out. The kids on TV (all of IT's victims) then start chanting "KILL THEM ALL! KILL THEM ALL!"

At the Marsh

Georgie's fate is terrible as it is actually depicted in the movie, and it partially drives the plot and you can feel his brother's remorse through out the whole movie.

It was also incredibly creepy, and quite scary sometimes, and I really didn't expect to be scared by this movie. Very good jumpscares and awesome atmosphere.

I want to watch it again so badly. So far my favourite movie of the year. It will be quite hard to do better than this but I cross my finger. Bill Skarsgard did a terrific job as Pennywise.

Don't even get me started on the Soundtrack. From the first song that Bill's Mother is playing on the piano to the emotional Blood Oath song the music was perfect. I can't stress enough how the Blood Oath scene was the best!! The song on that scene, the growth from the kids and the feel that they are never going to be reunited that way again adds an emotional weight to that scene that no other movie could ever achieve. Makes me tear up every time I hear that song and remember about that moment! This isn't just a simple scary film, it's a coming of age story with a deep meaning: fear holds you back. You have to dare and live every day at it's fullest and don't be afraid. Thank you Muschiettis and the crew. You've created a masterpiece. Can't wait for chapter 2!!

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: Skardsgard wishes he could be Pennywise as much as this movie wishes it could be IT. We don't become enamored with the kids individually like we did in the original. If not for having watched the original I would not have known which kid was which even halfway through the film. None seemed very special to me and they tried to make us like them by having them curse and make sexual mother jokes way too often. I also didn't appreciate how they diminished Mike Hanlon's role in this one and giving what made his character so special over to Ben Hanscom. I wonder what that's about. I mean Ben has issues that define his character already. Skarsgard blatantly tries to make his voice sound like something scary but fails miserably. This Bill can't hold a candle to Johnathan Brandis. I couldn't care less if he died or about how he felt about Georgie's death which he didn't seem to mourn over about much as in the original. The film isn't scary at all and relies more on jump scares than actual horror. Huge fail of a remake and doesn't capture my heart and imagination like the original. Ruins one of my favorite films of all time and makes me wonder how it and its characters have gotten such undeserved praise.

Comment: Also one more thing, as a kid of the 80's, I did not feel in this film like I was being taken back to 1989. Sure kids are kids and they don't always talk decent at times, because they are kids, and kids want to rebel a bit from what is supposed to be proper and what is not, however the vulgarity they used when they would talk in certain conversations and their sarcasm with each other in this film, reminded me of the way the disrespectful youths you hear talk of today, so it took away from the innocence of the kids in this film that they made for the new IT movie. When you compare to the original IT movie, where they had the kids growing up, I think took place around the 50'r or early 60's, where the kids were like typical children of that time period. A more innocent time period of children in those days. In the original film I believe it was far more accurate. Just my opinion.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: I was really disappointed with this movie. To me the original was far better, maybe because it had less special affects in it, and gave more of the story line. For instance, in the original IT movie, the scene where it shows the boys riding, fast to get away from something so scary, you can't see it, but in your mind you built up this image of something so horrifying, that it leaves you hanging on the edge of your seat! Tim Curry did a superb job as Pennywise the clown, of course he was a more experienced actor, and not to put down the new guy, just I don't think anyone can take the place of Tim Curry's performance of being Pennywise.  It's like they over tried to make it scary, and just like so many horror movies these days, it sucked, because they forget sometimes too much special affects in my opinion can ruin a movie, because it leaves nothing left to the imagination, where you build up something far more sinister in your mind, and scares the hell out of you! Actually one of the most scariest parts of the original IT was when Pennywise disguised himself as a gas station attendant, because they make the scene at first seem so innocent, like just a normal thing, you have to stop to get gas, but then when he gives the woman directions, and his voice changes and mixes with that of Pennywise, and what made it so scary just by something so simple, by just changing the guys voice. To me sometimes simple things like this, are far more frightening, and makes me a bit apprehensive about stopping for gas at some small country gas station, where you have one attendant working. LOL!

Comment: This movie is fantastic, it is the perfect combination of scary, comedic, romantic, and gorey. The acting is phenomenal and very realistic and relatable, they are not perfect at all down to their facial expressions which made the movie very enjoyable. The jumpscares involved in the movie were not pointless like many are, but actually quite creepy and detailed along with each child's personal monster. This was one of the best movies i have ever seen, i could watch it a hundred times over and not get bored! Every time you watch it again, you pick up something you missed the last time and it never fails to please, even for people who dislike scary movies, i assure you this movie you will love!

Comment:
Just saw it last night. Honestly, I was very impressed and I think they did a great job with this one. I've read the book and listened to it on audible a few times. I've watched the 1990s version and 
I really  like the casting for this 2017 remake and felt that they all played their characters incredibly well.

This movie had plenty of fright and creepiness to it but its not over the top. It has many jump-scare scenes but they didn't go overboard with it. It is a well-acted movie and the story has a great emotional touch to it. The movie did not mirror the book completely or as detailed, but it was exceptional in depicting the brilliance and dark, wicked creativity of Stephen King.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: This was the greatest movie I have ever seen! I went with my mom last night, who is a huge Steven King fan. I haven't read a Steven King book yet, and my mom read IT when she was about 12, my age. We went to see the Dark Tower about a month or two ago, and while we were driving back from the theatre, she was telling me about all the left out things and missed opportunities. But, on the drive back from the theatre after IT, she told me about how much it followed the book, and while watching the movie she was reminded of things in the book. And I, someone who hasn't read the book, was able to follow the movie and enjoy  IT. To be completely honest, this is probably not the scariest movie ever. I was able to get to sleep last night just fine. IT uses lots of jump scares, but not cheap ones that lose their scariness after two times. They still surprise you, and the jump scares used creepy imagery. And it's not just Pennywise jump scares, there are other creatures too. You should also know that there is plenty of blood in the movie, and not so much guts and gore. The closest there is to gore is in the beginning where (spoiler alert) Pennywise bites off Georgie's arm, and Georgie tries to crawl away using his bitten-off arm and his unhurt arm. But that's about it. This movie is more of a physiological horror than a torture movie. So, if you're into that, whether your a Steven King fan or not, or have read the book or not, go watch IT.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
Just watched IT and I gotta say to anyone who thinks it'll suck it won't! I promise! The movie was really well made and does the novel justice. The humor in this movie was also what was great about it! You'd think it'd be just a bunch of kids doing lame shit, but I assure you! IT's totally not! Just the first 10 mins of the movie got me really messed up lol. There were even some scenes that were really terrifying. While watching this, just another heads up, try to pay attention to the subtle details in the movie, cause if you've read the novel by Stephen King, then just wait and see, cause Chapter 2 will be on a whole nava level, lol. I can totally say it was well made to the point you aren't feeling bored, its very entertaining and another thing the music in the movie was really good too! So as a person who loves the horror genre and know this, in the last few years with a shitty bunch of horror movies out, this isn't one of those. Also, best part! No shitty jump scares! Bill Skarsgard did a great job as Pennywise no doubt! Tim Curry would not be disappointed! Anyways, sorry for the long ass comment! But I had to! I usually go back to trailers of movies that are really good to leave a comment such as this so people who aren't just watching the trailer and not knowing what the movie will exactly be like, well heres a guy who is part of the "losers club" :D 

TL;DR. Really good movie, go watch, won't be disappointed!

I just watched this. HIGHLY recommend IT.  A very disturbing and haunting film. Also nostalgic for so many reasons personally. Pennywise's 2017 take is so current and creepy AF. By far one of the best Stephen's King adaptations. 

Little Georgie's iconic opening scene getting has armed ripped off and dragged down the street gutter (eaten) is an absolutely terrifying and heartbreaking scene for me. I can still remember every detail of the scene. So disturbing on so many levels even into my adulthood.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
I thought the movie was good. It was much scarier than a lot of recent horror movies/ tv shows that try to replace horror with gore etc. Pennywise was definitely very well acted and the scenarios portrayed exactly the kind of separation and oppression a demon does to it's victims to gain trust and feed on their fear before taking the person over... or in this case to eat for movie purposes. I think if this movie was the first version of it created with then no one would say a word otherwise.
The original movie, lacked the technology that gave more abilities to this movie which gave it more to the actors to show and relate to to feel the fear as they did. While we get th at as well with a great cast, we also had more visually to aid in that as well..

Most scariest .movie ever? No. 
Acting scale 1-10 ? I give it a 9
Scare factor 1-10? Solid 8. I agree it could have been a little more frightening . 

Overall I give it a 9 out of ten. Really played to each fear well and better storytelling as well as better true horror appeal than recent movies.

This new Pennywise has to be the scariest movie monster we've seen in years. Literally years. There's two scenes in this movie that absolutely sent shivers down my spine. First when Pennywise possesses the slideshow and we finally get to see his very creepy and mental face in the final scene. What a build-up! I nearly pissed myself.

The other one is in the basement, first we see the excellent performance by Georgie's actor. You'll float too never has sounded more epically scary. And then Pennywise rises from the waters. I jumped in my chair and still do when watching this. I can tell I will be on the edge of my seat in theatres this september.

The movie itself seems to capture that 80s feeling we've seen in Stranger Things and other important work. Do your part and see it in theaters. Be a part of history.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
I'm glad this is going to be R-rated, as it should be. Not PG-13. Directly after the boat clip featured in the trailer, Pennywise rips Georgie's arm off...causing his death. 

"Blood flowed into the storm drain from the tattered hole where his left arm had been. A knob of bone, horribly bright, peeked through the torn cloth."

I'm not sure they'll include this as graphically in the film, but, a novel as sinister and dark as this one deserves adult treatment. What's worrying is that many here still believe it's a remake, rather than a fresh adaptation - because they forget that books exist. Also, it's not just "another horror film" to be placed beside generic box office hits; it's an imagining of one of the scariest stories ever written. Definitely not "a creepy clown flick". IT is so much more than that. 

Anyway, let's hope it ruins our ability to sleep.

Comment:
Here we see yet another Stephen King movie from Stephen King Book Mills, inc.. He has entertaining enough stuff, but let's face it: h e is virtually always churning out derivatives off of other people's earlier works.

I'd not be surprised to see his studio fill of writers laboring under his "tutelage", like so many Thomas Kinkade-esque studios invariably degenerate into. 

Yes, simply rehash old themes, it's marketed as "New and Original out of NYC of Hollyweird", but really, it's all about as original as this latest reboot. 

Remember back when it was: Ohhh, it's set in Maine! What an original twist!, How unique! How creepy! Not so ,much. See: Dark Shadows, (1966) Whispering Gables (1968): Hunter's Hill (1973) The Glory Hand (1983)

"IT" (written:1986)  derives from the likes of:  Carnival of Souls (1962) The Clown Murders (1976) Poltergeist (1982). I'm astonished that he's not been sued for copyright infringement. 

Oh wait, he's being sued right now for Plagiarism for a character in "Dork Tower". I'd bet TWO things about King; he settles out of court and never had to sue someone else for plagiarizing his plagiarisms, lolz.. 

"Apparently about 60+ things from Duma Key would look like Ron Marquardt's"Keller's Den" book, published in 2002." (coutrhousenews,com)

Go compare: The Running Man to The Prize of Peril (1958). Oh, a thrid bet, I bet you can find more! :)

 implied or hinted at,  but we'll see.

Comment:
between the research and trailers I've seen, stories like this require atmosphere and a foreboding tone, not blood and guts.  I like the 90s miniseries
but I'd like to see how this one would work as well.  It looks like Pennywise is gonna be a lot less chatty but hopefully not It's primary form, and I'm also hoping
for more build up scares, and more story line. Don't misunderstand me, I like the miniseries, and will attempt to avoid comparisons...but on home media 
probably for me.   Splitting it up like Peter Jackson did with Lord of the Rings and The Hobbit may work, but not a whole years waiting time, just an idea.
  The newer clown images look a lot more foreboding and ominous...for a modern audience, but we'll see.

Comment:
**********SPOILER ALERT DO NOT READ IF YOU DON'T WANT TO BE SPOILED********

While I really do think (and hope) that they follow the book more closely in this one, there is one scene I HOPE they don't include. But since it's now confirmed that it's rated R, I'm worried they will. All of you readers of the original 'IT' book probably know what I'm talking about. I believe chapter 28-when Stephan King thought it was a great idea to include all the kids having a giant orgy with Bev to 'lose their innocence' and get out alive. Like...please, don't. It wasn't okay when you wrote it, it sure as fuck isn't going to settle well now. I love Stephan King, but he's notorious for shitty endings. And that one scene in IT almost ruined the whole series, which was AMAZING leading up to it.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: The "you'll float too" thing is genius, c'mon. At first the voice is a one of pure joy - the creature like It that is so evil by nature honestly loves murdering and is anticipating. But then the voice gets more persistent, more enraged, because the characters struggle and don't want to "float". It shows the fight between the Losers and It, and how their resistance frustrates the monster.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: Before I started reading "IT" a couple months ago, I saw the first trailer and was convinced this wasn't going to be as good the miniseries, which I loved as a kid. But now that I've read it I'm convinced that this is going to be way more accurate--if not way better. Can't wait to watch it. Dunno how I feel about Pennywise's voice yet, but I imagine it'll grow on me in time. Either way, it's much closer to how he's written in King's book than the Tim Curry version, as much as I enjoyed his performance.

Comment: Ok here's the HUGE PROBLEM with this... the clown is NOT supposed to be scary, he's supposed to be friendly and Inviting! Sure you'll think it's still creepy and weird because it's a clown for no reason but he's evil in the sense that he wants you to join him and you willingly follow... this is just ruining the whole idea of the evil in this movie, you're making the villain an Obvious bad guy... rather than a creepy friendly clown who happens to be evil beneath the surface. Comment: So what's up with all of the hate for looking too much like Stranger Things?  Yes, this is set in the 1980s and Finn Wolfhard is in it.  But Stranger Things was inspired by Stephen King's works in the first place.  The creators wanted to direct It but were turned down because they weren't "established" enough.  Finn Wolfhard was cast in the movie before Stranger Things wen Cary Fukanaga was attached to the movie.  He left the project and production was on hold again for rewrites.  Wolfhard was then cast in Stranger Things, filmed that, then came back to It when Andres Muschietti was attached to the movie and cast the movie.

Comment:
It's eyes are not both centered, and I've noticed this in multiple trailers and multiple scenes. Either:

1. The CGI is just garbage and they can't orient the eyes correctly, or

2. One eye is consistently focused on the camera (i.e. the viewer) intentionally, so as to give the impression that It knows you are there and everything happening is intended for him to be speaking to you.

Very much think it's the former, but would be presently surprised if they're going for the latter.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: Expectations are super low as they should be considering that good horror films are rare these days. However I will keep an open mind. Pennywise looks great and the kid actors chosen look like they can carry a film. The aspect of the adults acting mysterious and pretending like there is no demon clown is a neat premise. My biggest concerns come down to writing and jumpscares. The story is simple but can be amazing if written well but again horror films have trouble with that. Then there's jumpscares, I hate this the most. Not because they scare me but because it is a cheap scare and when given to the wrong writers will bring about the fake-out jumpscare which is worse. A couple sprinkled in will be fine but if every encounter with Pennywise is a damn jumpscare then I'm out. The best horror moments come from atmosphere, setting, lighting, the presence of the threat, errie ambient noises, and just the sound design in general. Let Pennywise be creepy, threatening, and terrifying without resorting to cheap flashes and loud bangs.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: I'm a huge Stephen King fan, and enjoyed the IT miniseries when I first watched it. Years later I read the book and while I still like the original adaptation, there's no doubt that they didn't do the story justice. There's so many great moments in the book that were left out or not explored. This looks like a more faithful adaptation and includes moments from the novel that fans will love to see on the screen. Plus I like that the film is split into two parts. The "Kids Story" and "Adults Story" are both super important but it's extremely difficult to include both in one film with losing a huge chunk of what makes IT great.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment: Have any of you naysayers actually READ the novel? Or are you just going off the in my opinion mediocre made for TV miniseries from the 90's??(expect Curry's good performance as Pennywise) This Pennywise looks EXACTLY how he was described in the book. The kids are dead on with their characters,Eddie as a hypochondriac and Richie as "The man of 1000 voices". The balloons look fake and super symmetrical because they're SUPPOSED TO. THEY'RE PART OF PENNYWISE'S ILLUSIONS. He isn't supposed to be friendly and inviting. He only appeared that way to one person: Georgie. In the novel, even the smallest children could sense that there was something g wrong about him. AND LET ME SAY IT AGAIN FOR THE IDIOTS IN THE BACK: THIS IS NOT A REMAKE OF THE MINISERIES. IT'S A NEW ADAPTATION OF THE NOVEL. If you want cheap thrills, go watch a stupid B horror flick and leave this promising masterpiece to the real King fans.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
Yay, another "Horror" Movie that relies on jump scare tactics. 
The original "IT", was back when audiences actually wanted a REAL scare that will make them afraid to turn off the lights at night. 
Today, our standards have dropped so low, that we are now satisfied with a quick "startle", and that's what counts as scary these days. 
The dread you feel when you see someone walking around a dimly lit basement where you already know the monster is, is just us bracing ourselves for that "peekaboo" moment. 
We literally already know it's coming. Lol!

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
0:46 This makes now the scene with Georgie more retarded than ever. 

I mean, I think on the Books (And specially on the Curry Miniseries) Pennywhise had one Clown Form that was friendly, kinda like "Ronald McDonalds" vibe. In the Miniseries itself was retarded to see Georgie trying to grab the paper boat from Pennywhise (A Clown that suddenly shown down there, but a Happy and "Friendly" Clown).

Now Pennywhise it's full on "Scary Mode". If I was that kid and saw THIS Pennywhise, I will run the fuck out and escape the country if needed. Georgie can't be THAT Stupid to TRUST on THIS Pennywhise, who's a "guy" with a Creepy AF Smile and Eyes and shit.

It kinda ruins the whole point of the scene and makes Georgie the King of The Retards. I can see HISHE playing with this scene if they do the "How "IT" Should have ended". 

I mean, Pennywhise has this "Scary Mode" version too...and the "Friendly Version" one too. Make him Full Scary makes him predictable, sorta. 

Let's hope they don't made "IT" The typical Screamer Movie too, because the ambientation looks neat and I would hate to see this movie (That haves potential) turned out to be some other "Scary" movie of this days.

Title: IT - Official Trailer 1
Comment:
Typical Hollywood over-worked "reboot/remake" (call "IT" whatever (excuse the pun)). Nice camera work, good looking cast and a shiny trailer to sell the product as usual. After all is said and done, as with all horror remakes, its just another Hollywood cash-in project just like all the rest. Theres no originality. Long gone are the 60s, 70s and 80s where horror had its best times and Hollywood steered clear of fucking everything up. 

Personally, ALL films made should have Copyright clauses stating no film can be remade within 50 years of the originals release date. That'd force screenwriters to actually invent new, fresh and plausible ideas. Or at least come up with something that isnt a reboot etc. Its films like this that are creating a stale environment for everyone, and everyone is stupid enough to fall for it. If we all steered clear of theatrical releases of reboots and boycotted their attempts at remakes, box office figures would be down, that would make Hollywood reassess what they are actually doing but people are to thick to think outside the box and you still throw money into the big wigs pockets. As good as people assume reboots may be, remember, for every reboot made, there are struggling filmmakers trying hard as hell to create a film on a minimal budget. This is a BAD thing for the film business. Hollywood have screwed up pretty much every horror remake. There are a few exceptions which mainly came out in the 80s, and a few in the 90s. Dont fall for this hype. As much as i love horror (been obsessed with it for over 30 yrs now) i have to steer clear of this film purely out of principal and also for the fact its hurting Indy film production because everyone expects big motion pictures where millions has been thrown at it. Give me cult 80s slasher films, giallo, underground horror, jap splatter, hammer horror (first run of filmmaking), Amicus productions and Indy work anyday. Thats whats important for the horror community. Thats where true horror lies with true passionate filmmakers who make films for the true horror fan, not the brainwashed general cinema goer who part with their hard-earned cash to fund future remakes.

If youre still not sold as to why remakes hurt the filmmaking business, take a look at what Hollywood did to the Original Blair Witch Project. No, im not on about the recent reboot (which also sucked balls), but im on about how quick Hollywood saw a money making opportunity and made Book of Shadows (Blair Witch 2). Within one year Hollywood threw a script together, filmed and released it. What. A. Joke! Just for the money. Blair 2 was utter garbage and failed miserably. No thought went  into it what so ever!Regardless whether you like or dislike the original Blair With Project, the fact remains that the internet was in its infancy back in '99. The whole marketing ploy behind TBWP was pure genious. This ploy can no longer be done but thanks to their clever marketing and website and Indy footage, The Blair Witch Project has gone on to be one of the higgest grossing films ever made when compared to the initial outlay costs.

Now, how many other cult classics have been screwed up by Hollywood? Well, the list is endless but you all bought in to it. Heres a few that sprung to mind:

Texas chainsaw massacre
Psycho
The ring
Day of the dead
Dawn of the dead
Hills have eyes
The crazies
Evil dead
Nightmare on elm street
Prom night
House of wax
Carrie
Black christmas
The hitcher
Friday 13th
The fog
Dark water
The wicker man
The Omen
Children of the corn
The eye
House on haunted hill

And so on....

Did you buy in to any of those? Some of you did. Why? Stop buying in to it. Support the originals, support Indy filmmakers and lets show Hollywood they cant do this crap anymore.

I love the original IT. The only time im going to see this is when it drops on Sky Movies or if i see it in a bargain bin for less than 3 quid.
